n <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ier","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and Norwegian vernacular form of   Peter ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Ier DE COURCELLES was born in 1180, in Le Breuil-sur-Couze, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne, France as the son of Gauzbert DE COURCELLES. He had at least 1 son with Mahaut DE BUSSY. He died in 1240, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1180–1240":"1180–1240","–Female":"Surnud","1200–1250":"1200–1250","–Male":"Surnud","environ 1200":"umbes 1200","1200":"1200","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1180":"1180","Le Breuil-sur-Couze, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne, França":"Le Breuil-sur-Couze, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne, Prantsusmaa","Le Breuil, Rhône, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Le Breuil, Rhône, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1180–1240":"1180–1240","–Female":"Kuollut","1200–1250":"1200–1250","–Male":"Kuollut","environ 1200":"noin 1200","1200":"1200","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1180":"1180","Le Breuil-sur-Couze, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne, França":"Le Breuil-sur-Couze, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne, Ranska","Le Breuil, Rhône, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Le Breuil, Rhône, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Ranska"},"fr":{"1180–1240":"1180–1240","–Female":"Décédée","1200–1250":"1200–1250","–Male":"Décédé","environ 1200":"environ 1200","1200":"1200","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1180":"1180","Le Breuil-sur-Couze, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne, França":"Le Breuil-sur-Couze, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne, France","Le Breuil, Rhône, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Le Breuil, Rhône, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France","lifeSummary":"Robert Ier DE COURCELLES est né en 1180, à Le Breuil-sur-Couze, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne, France, fils de Gauzbert DE COURCELLES. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Mahaut DE BUSSY. Il est décédé en 1240, à l’âge de 60 ans."},"de":{"1180–1240":"1180–1240","–Female":"Verstorben","1200–1250":"1200–1250","–Male":"Verstorben","environ 1200":"um 1200","1200":"1200","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1180":"1180","Le Breuil-sur-Couze, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne, França":"Le Breuil-sur-Couze, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne, Frankreich","Le Breuil, Rhône, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Le Breuil, Rhône, Au